== Commissioning

=== Cryostat Commissioning
- The physical assembly of the CUORE cryostat proceeded in parallel with the data-taking operations of CUORE-0, reaching structural completion in early 2014. Following the decommissioning of CUORE-0, an exhaustive (*?*) cryostat commissioning phase began. This involved multiple cooldowns designed to test and characterize major subsystems individually, with each cryogenic cycle spanning several months.
- These commissioning runs progressively scaled in complexity:
  - Initial tests strictly verified the dilution refrigerator's capacity to reach base temperature and tested the electronic readout chain.
  - Subsequent runs integrated a "mini-tower" consisting of just 8 instrumented crystals.
  - A comprehensive end-to-end test of the cryostat was performed with both the mini-tower and the top lead shield installed on the Tower Support Plate (TSP). During this run, the cryostat reached a base temperature below 7 mK. Using inserted calibration strings, the system successfully recorded particle pulses, resolving the 2615 keV $208$Tl gamma peak with an energy resolution of $~10$ keV FWHM.
  - This critical run also provided essential diagnostic data used to map and mitigate mechanical vibrations and electrical noise across the system.
- The fourth major test run introduced the massive lateral Roman lead shield at the 4 K stage. While cooling a staggering cold mass of 19 tonnes down to 4 K, the system achieved a stable base temperature of 6.3 mK.

=== Installation

- Following the cryogenic commissioning, the delicate detector installation phase commenced in the summer of 2016. This was arguably the most critical operational phase of the entire experiment. It required meticulous logistical planning to protect the pristine #teo2 crystals from radioactive re-contamination while operators safely manipulated a fragile, deeply interconnected system comprising tens of thousands of components.
- To facilitate this, the first floor of the hut was converted into a multi-room environment with strictly controlled cleanliness levels. This included a high-grade cleanroom (Class 10/1000) that housed the cryostat top plate and served as the tower assembly area.
- Prior to installation, the fully assembled towers had been securely stored in the cleanroom inside custom containers constantly flushed with $N_2$ gas. Transferring them to the TSP was the singular moment they were exposed to ambient cleanroom air. To mitigate this, the air was processed by a dedicated radon abatement system, and environmental radon levels were logged continuously throughout the installation phase.
- The tower installation process adhered to exceptionally strict protocols:
  - Each tower required a full working day to mechanically and electrically install. Upon securing a tower, it (*? single tower?*) was immediately sealed within an $N_2$-flushed protective bag to prevent further atmospheric exposure.
  - To minimize contamination and dust disturbance, the specialized installation team was prohibited from entering or exiting the cleanroom during a tower's installation, necessitating unique procedures for in-room hydration and sustenance.
  - An independent oversight team continuously monitored and logged every motion of the operation.
- The entire installation phase was successfully completed in just over a month, concluding on August 26, 2016. Remarkably, out of the 988 channels, only 8 were initially identified as problematic. Half of these were successfully repaired *in situ*, leaving only 4 channels irreparably broken.
- Following the final verification of the Detector Control System (DCS), the cryostat was permanently sealed.
- The first full cooldown of the completed CUORE experiment commenced on December 5, 2016. The Fast Cooling System (FCS) was activated first, followed by the Pulse Tubes four days later, successfully chilling the entire mass to 3.4 K in approximately 22 days.
- The Dilution Unit (DU) was subsequently engaged in early January 2017, smoothly driving the vast experimental volume down to an operational base temperature of 6.9 mK over 26 days.
- Concluding the commissioning phase, the very first physical background pulses from the fully integrated array were successfully recorded on January 26–27, 2017.
